#. Tag: title
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:11
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; Overview"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:12
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &deng; is a lightweight virtualization solution to run multiple virtual Linux environments (containers) simultaneously on top of a single Linux kernel, without a hypervisor. Containers are isolated using Kernel cgroups ( <xref linkend=\"vle-docker-cgroup\"/> ) and <xref linkend=\"vle-docker-namespace\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:18
#, no-c-format
msgid "Full virtualization solutions, such as &xen;, &kvm;, or &libvirt;, are based on simulating a complete hardware environment and running multiple operating system instances inside these virtual machines. The &deng; provides operating-system-level virtualization: a single Linux kernel controls multiple isolated containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:25
#, no-c-format
msgid "The &deng; allows developers and system administrators to manage the complete life cycle of images. The &deng; makes it easy to build, ship, and run images containing applications."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:30
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; has the following advantages:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:35
#, no-c-format
msgid "Isolation of applications through containers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:40
#, no-c-format
msgid "Near-native performance, as the &deng; manages allocation of resources in real time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:46
#, no-c-format
msgid "Control network interfaces and resources available inside containers through cgroups."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid "Versioning of images."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:57
#, no-c-format
msgid "Building new images based on existing ones."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:62
#, no-c-format
msgid "Container orchestration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:67
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; has the following limitations:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:72
#, no-c-format
msgid "Containers run on the host system's kernel and cannot use a different kernel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid "Only supports Linux applications and not other operating systems."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:83
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; is not a full virtualization stack like &xen;, &kvm;, or &libvirt;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:88
#, no-c-format
msgid "Security depends on the host system. Refer to the <link xlink:href=\"http://docs.docker.com/articles/security/\">official security documentation</link> for more details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:96
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; Architecture"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: containers-docker-overview.xml:98
#, no-c-format
msgid "&deng; uses a client/server architecture. You can use the <emphasis>CLI client</emphasis> to communicate with the <emphasis>daemon</emphasis> . The <emphasis>daemon</emphasis> performs operations with containers and manages images locally or in registry. The <emphasis>CLI client</emphasis> can run on the same server as the host daemon or on a different machine. The <emphasis>CLI client</emphasis> communicates with the <emphasis>daemon</emphasis> by using network sockets. The architecture is shown in <xref linkend=\"fig-docker-architecture\"/> ."
msgstr ""

